{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612486"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:25:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:25:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0,0.06,0.74,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8972"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114422"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8972"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6659"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21349"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21354"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22680"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114422"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal carotid artery follows a complex course through the skull base before entering the cranial cavity. After emerging from the cavernous sinus, it gives off several important branches.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the first branch that is given off as it emerges from this site?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior ethmoidal","Central retinal","Lacrimal","Ophthalmic","Supraorbital"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eophthalmic artery\u003C/strong\u003E is the first branch of the internal carotid artery after it emerges from the cavernous sinus. It enters the orbit through the optic canal, accompanying the optic nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are actually branches of the ophthalmic artery. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elacrimal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the lacrimal gland and adjacent structures. The \u003Cstrong\u003Esupraorbital artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the forehead and scalp. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior ethmoidal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the anterior ethmoidal air cells and anterior meninges. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecentral retinal artery\u003C/strong\u003E supplies the retina. The internal carotid artery continues to give off other important branches including the posterior communicating artery, anterior cerebral artery, and middle cerebral artery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ophthalmic artery is the first branch of the internal carotid artery after it emerges from the cavernous sinus.","The ophthalmic artery enters the orbit through the optic canal alongside the optic nerve.","Major branches of the ophthalmic artery include the central retinal, lacrimal, supraorbital and ethmoidal arteries."],"references":["Sethi D, Gofur EM, Munakomi S. Anatomy, Head and Neck: Carotid Arteries. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545238/","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T15:37:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T15:37:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8972"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114422"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":nul